\b IAM Team Assessment Workbook\b0\par
\par
Assigned controls: AC-2 Account Management and IA-5 Authenticator Management.\par
Primary teams: IAM, Security Engineering, HR Operations, IT Administration.\par
\par
\b AC-2 Account Management\b0\par
Objective: Ensure system accounts are defined, approved, provisioned, monitored, reviewed, and removed in a controlled lifecycle.\par
\par
1. Allowed and prohibited account types are defined and documented.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
2. Account managers are formally assigned.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
3. Group and role membership prerequisites are documented.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
4. Authorized users, memberships, privileges, and attributes are specified.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
5. Account creation requires approval by authorized personnel.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
6. Account lifecycle actions follow defined procedures.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
7. Account usage is monitored.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
8. Account managers are notified when need or status changes.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
9. Access authorization is based on valid authorization and intended usage.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
10. Accounts are periodically reviewed for compliance.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
11. Shared or group authenticators are changed when membership changes.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
12. Account lifecycle is aligned to transfer and termination processes.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
\par
Evidence requests: access control policy, joiner mover leaver procedure, access approvals, account inventory, access reviews, deprovisioning records, shared account rotation evidence, usage monitoring reports.\par
Repo gap note: API requests default to anonymous when no user ID is supplied.\par
\par
\b IA-5 Authenticator Management\b0\par
Objective: Manage the issuance, protection, refresh, revocation, and secure handling of authenticators.\par
\par
1. Identity is verified before initial authenticator issuance.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
2. Initial authenticator content is established and controlled.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
3. Authenticators are strong enough for intended use.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
4. Procedures exist for issuance, compromise, damage, and revocation.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
5. Default authenticators are changed prior to first use.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
6. Authenticators are changed or refreshed on schedule and on triggering events.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
7. Authenticator content is protected from unauthorized disclosure or modification.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
8. Users and devices are required to protect authenticators.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
9. Group and role authenticators are changed when membership changes.\par
Status: ____________________  Evidence: ____________________\par
Notes: ________________________________________________________________\par
\par
Evidence requests: authenticator standard, MFA procedures, default credential checklist, rotation records, secret storage design, revocation records.\par
Repo gap note: No application authentication flow or MFA enforcement is visible.\par
\par
\b Baseline Focus\b0\par
Low impact: IA-5 includes IA-5(1).\par
Moderate impact: AC-2 includes AC-2(1), (2), (3), (4), (5), (13); IA-5 includes IA-5(1), (2), (6).\par
